    <segment id="1" parent="2" relname="solutionhood">Steve.Fuller@durham.ac.uk wrote Oct. 10 from Charlottesville VA
&amp;gt;REPLY TO SHANKS AND RICHARDSON ON ENEMIES OF SCIENCE:
&amp;gt;
&amp;gt;Nobody is denying that philosophical considerations have informed and 
&amp;gt;motivated scientific work. In fact, it would be hard to comprehend the 
&amp;gt;point of doing science without smuggling in philosophy. However, there 
&amp;gt;are still a few open questions. First, whether scientists really need a 
&amp;gt;class of people called &apos;philosophers of science&apos; to help them with their 
&amp;gt;philosophizing. Second, whether philosophers of science should be in the 
&amp;gt;business of &apos;helping scientists&apos; rather than doing something a bit more 
&amp;gt;independent and/or critical. . . .</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="20" relname="span">

There are obvious answers to Fuller&apos;s enumerated questions.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="13" relname="span">  First, there
appears to be ample evidence that scientists do not need philosophers&apos;
help to do good science; </segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="elaboration"> and usually derive any related philosophy
directly from the science rather than through the discipline of philosophy. </segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="13" relname="background">
(Peter Medawar has commented on this.)</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="7" relname="concession">  Second, one may test
for &quot;helpfulness&quot; in any enterprise by asking the views of either the
helpers or the people helped: </segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="19" relname="span"> but it would be naive to expect these tests
to be equivalent.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="9" relname="concession">

In Canada where the discipline of &quot;political science&quot; is old and strong,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="17" relname="span"> I
see a similar relation. </segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="16" relname="span"> The PS discipline needs politicians to keep going
but not vice versa.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="12" relname="antithesis">  (Politicians will cite PS when to their advantage,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="15" relname="span">
but have no functional need for its scholarly activity or people.)</segment>
